---
import PageShell from '../../../../components/PageShell.astro';
import CTABox from '../../../../components/CTABox.astro';
import ComparisonTable from '../../../../components/ComparisonTable.astro';

const tocItems = [
  { id: 'overview', text: 'Overview', level: 2 },
  { id: 'healthcare-system', text: 'Healthcare System', level: 2 },
  { id: 'visa-requirements', text: 'Visa Options', level: 2 },
  { id: 'insurance-requirements', text: 'Insurance Requirements', level: 2 },
  { id: 'recommended-providers', text: 'Recommended Providers', level: 2 },
  { id: 'costs', text: 'Expected Costs', level: 2 },
  { id: 'scenarios', text: 'Real-World Scenarios', level: 2 },
  { id: 'faqs', text: 'Common Questions', level: 2 },
];

const relatedLinks = [
  { text: 'Greece for Seniors', href: '/insurance-for/seniors/in/greece' },
  { text: 'Italy for Seniors', href: '/insurance-for/seniors/in/italy' },
  { text: 'Spain for Seniors', href: '/insurance-for/seniors/in/spain' },
  { text: 'Portugal for Seniors', href: '/insurance-for/seniors/in/portugal' },
];

const providerColumns = [
  { key: 'provider', header: 'Provider' },
  { key: 'maxAge', header: 'Max Entry Age' },
  { key: 'coverage', header: 'Coverage Type' },
  { key: 'croatiaNetwork', header: 'Croatia Network' },
  { key: 'euAccess', header: 'EU Coverage' },
  { key: 'annualCost', header: 'Annual Cost (65yo)' },
];

const providerRows = [
  { provider: 'Cigna Global', maxAge: '74', coverage: 'Comprehensive', croatiaNetwork: 'Zagreb hospitals, Adriatic clinics', euAccess: 'Included', annualCost: '$4,200-6,800' },
  { provider: 'Allianz Care', maxAge: '74', coverage: 'Comprehensive', croatiaNetwork: 'Good coverage', euAccess: 'Included', annualCost: '$4,000-6,500' },
  { provider: 'AXA Global', maxAge: '74', coverage: 'Comprehensive', croatiaNetwork: 'Wide network', euAccess: 'Included', annualCost: '$3,800-6,200' },
  { provider: 'Bupa Global', maxAge: '74', coverage: 'Premium', croatiaNetwork: 'Major hospitals', euAccess: 'Included', annualCost: '$5,200-8,500' },
  { provider: 'IMG Global', maxAge: '74', coverage: 'Flexible', croatiaNetwork: 'Reimbursement', euAccess: 'Available', annualCost: '$3,200-5,500' },
];

const costColumns = [
  { key: 'category', header: 'Expense Category' },
  { key: 'lowEstimate', header: 'Budget Option' },
  { key: 'midEstimate', header: 'Mid-Range' },
  { key: 'highEstimate', header: 'Premium' },
];

const costRows = [
  { category: 'International Health Insurance', lowEstimate: '$3,200/year', midEstimate: '$5,000/year', highEstimate: '$8,000+/year' },
  { category: 'Private GP Visit', lowEstimate: '€30-50', midEstimate: '€50-80', highEstimate: '€80-120' },
  { category: 'Specialist Consultation', lowEstimate: '€50-90', midEstimate: '€90-140', highEstimate: '€140-200' },
  { category: 'Hospital Day (Private)', lowEstimate: '€200-350', midEstimate: '€350-550', highEstimate: '€550-850' },
  { category: 'Prescription Medications', lowEstimate: '30-50% US prices', midEstimate: '30-50% US prices', highEstimate: '30-50% US prices' },
  { category: 'Dental Crown', lowEstimate: '€250-400', midEstimate: '€400-600', highEstimate: '€600-850' },
];
---

<PageShell
  title="Health Insurance for Seniors in Croatia | Expat Guide 2025"
  description="Complete guide to health insurance for retirees and seniors in Croatia. Compare international providers, understand visa requirements, and plan your Adriatic coast retirement."
  headline="Health Insurance for Seniors in Croatia"
  subheadline="Your guide to healthcare coverage on the stunning Adriatic coast"
  heroImage="/images/countries/croatia-hero-bg.png"
  tocItems={tocItems}
  relatedLinks={relatedLinks}
>
  <section id="overview" class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Overview</h2>
    <p class="mb-4">
      Croatia has emerged as an increasingly attractive retirement destination, offering Mediterranean climate, stunning Adriatic coastline, EU membership, and costs lower than Western Europe. The country joined the Schengen Area in 2023 and adopted the Euro, simplifying travel and finances for expat retirees.
    </p>
    <p class="mb-4">
      For seniors, Croatia offers a unique combination: the beauty and lifestyle of Italy or Greece at 30-40% lower costs. Historic towns like Dubrovnik, Split, and Zadar provide Mediterranean living with growing expat communities. Zagreb offers urban amenities with continental climate. The coast itself stretches over 1,000 islands, offering endless exploration.
    </p>
    <p class="mb-4">
      Healthcare in Croatia is good by European standards, with Zagreb hosting the country's best medical facilities. The public healthcare system (HZZO) provides comprehensive coverage, while a growing private sector offers premium options. For highly specialized care, neighboring Austria, Italy, and Germany are easily accessible.
    </p>
    <p>
      The expat retirement community is smaller than in Spain or Portugal but growing. English proficiency is reasonable, especially along the tourist coast and among younger professionals. German and Italian are also widely understood. The slower pace of life and genuine hospitality appeal to those seeking authentic European living without the crowds of more established retirement destinations.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section id="healthcare-system" class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Healthcare System Overview</h2>
    <p class="mb-4">
      Croatia operates a mandatory health insurance system through HZZO (Croatian Health Insurance Fund). The system covers all residents and provides comprehensive public healthcare. Quality is generally good, though resources concentrate in Zagreb and larger cities.
    </p>
    <p class="mb-4">
      Zagreb hosts the country's premier medical facilities. KBC Zagreb (Clinical Hospital Center Zagreb) is the largest and most comprehensive. University Hospital Sisters of Mercy, and University Hospital Dubrava provide specialized services. These facilities handle complex procedures including cardiac surgery, oncology, and transplants.
    </p>
    <p class="mb-4">
      Coastal regions have good general hospitals in Split, Rijeka, and Dubrovnik, plus numerous polyclinics (poliklinika) for outpatient care. However, complex cases often require transfer to Zagreb. For serious illness while living on the coast, the possibility of needing Zagreb care should factor into planning.
    </p>
    <p class="mb-4">
      Private healthcare is growing rapidly. Facilities like Special Hospital Sv. Katarina, Polyclinic Medikol, and Polyclinic Aviva offer premium services with shorter waits. Dental tourism is established, with clinics in Zagreb and along the coast attracting European patients.
    </p>
    <p>
      For highly specialized care—rare conditions, cutting-edge treatments, complex transplants—Austrian and German hospitals are accessible. Vienna and Munich are common referral destinations. Insurance with EU coverage enables these options when Croatia's resources are insufficient.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section id="visa-requirements" class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Visa Options for Senior Expats</h2>
    <p class="mb-4">
      As an EU and Schengen member since 2023, Croatia follows European immigration frameworks. EU citizens have straightforward residence rights. Non-EU citizens have several pathways, including a new Digital Nomad Visa that some retirees with passive income have utilized creatively.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-800 mb-3 mt-6">Temporary Residence for Private Purposes</h3>
    <p class="mb-4">
      Non-EU retirees typically apply for temporary residence on grounds of "private purposes" (osobni razlozi). This requires proof of sufficient financial means (no official minimum, but €1,500-2,000/month demonstrated income is practical), health insurance, and accommodation. Initial permits are for one year, renewable annually. After 5 years, permanent residence is possible.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-800 mb-3 mt-6">Digital Nomad Visa</h3>
    <p class="mb-4">
      While designed for remote workers, some retirees with investment income have used Croatia's Digital Nomad Visa (requiring €3,500/month income from foreign sources). This provides 1-year residence renewable for another year. Not technically a retirement visa, but functions similarly for those with sufficient passive income.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-800 mb-3 mt-6">EU Citizens</h3>
    <p class="mb-4">
      EU citizens can register for temporary residence after 3 months, requiring only proof of sufficient resources and health insurance (no specific minimum). After 5 years of continuous residence, permanent residence is available.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-800 mb-3 mt-6">Required Documents</h3>
    <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4 space-y-1">
      <li>Valid passport with at least 6 months validity</li>
      <li>Criminal background check (apostilled)</li>
      <li>Proof of income (pension statements, investment accounts)</li>
      <li>Proof of accommodation (ownership or rental contract)</li>
      <li>Health insurance valid in Croatia</li>
      <li>Application fee (approx €70)</li>
      <li>Biometric photo</li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      Health insurance is mandatory for residence applications. Coverage must be comprehensive for Croatia. International insurance is accepted. Once resident, you may be able to enroll in HZZO (public system) by paying contributions, but international coverage remains valuable for private care and European access.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section id="insurance-requirements" class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Insurance Requirements for Seniors</h2>
    <p class="mb-4">
      Croatia requires health insurance for residence applications. Beyond visa compliance, your insurance choices shape your healthcare experience—public system access, private facility options, and European referral capabilities.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-800 mb-3 mt-6">Public System (HZZO) Access</h3>
    <p class="mb-4">
      Legal residents can enroll in HZZO by paying monthly contributions (based on income, minimum approximately €250-300/month for those without Croatian employment income). Once enrolled, you have access to the public healthcare system with small copays. Coverage is comprehensive but wait times for non-urgent care can be lengthy.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-800 mb-3 mt-6">Why International Insurance Makes Sense</h3>
    <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4 space-y-2">
      <li><strong>Visa compliance:</strong> Required for initial application regardless of later HZZO enrollment</li>
      <li><strong>Private access:</strong> Skip public system waits with direct private hospital access</li>
      <li><strong>European referrals:</strong> Complex cases may require Vienna, Munich, or other EU centers</li>
      <li><strong>Travel coverage:</strong> Seamless protection throughout Schengen and beyond</li>
      <li><strong>Coastal coverage:</strong> Private options along the coast when Zagreb is far</li>
    </ul>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-800 mb-3 mt-6">Recommended Coverage Levels</h3>
    <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4 space-y-2">
      <li><strong>Overall maximum:</strong> $1-2 million (standard for Europe)</li>
      <li><strong>Hospital room:</strong> Private room coverage for inpatient stays</li>
      <li><strong>Emergency evacuation:</strong> $50,000+ for transport to Austrian/German specialist centers</li>
      <li><strong>Outpatient coverage:</strong> Useful for private specialist access</li>
      <li><strong>European coverage:</strong> Essential for accessing larger EU medical centers</li>
    </ul>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-800 mb-3 mt-6">HZZO + International Strategy</h3>
    <p>
      Many expats combine approaches: enroll in HZZO for basic public system access, then maintain international insurance for private care and European options. HZZO handles routine care and emergencies; international coverage provides speed, choice, and cross-border capability. This hybrid approach optimizes both cost and access.
    </p>
  </section>

  <CTABox
    title="Find Your Croatia Coverage"
    description="Compare international health insurance plans from providers with strong European networks. Get personalized quotes that provide Croatia coverage plus Austrian and German specialist access."
    buttonText="Compare Plans for Croatia"
    buttonHref="/get-quotes"
    variant="highlight"
  />

  <section id="recommended-providers" class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Recommended Insurance Providers</h2>
    <p class="mb-4">
      Croatia's EU and Schengen membership means international insurers operate smoothly. European network strength matters—neighboring Austria and Germany are the primary referral destinations for complex care.
    </p>

    <ComparisonTable columns={providerColumns} rows={providerRows} />

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-800 mb-3 mt-6">Provider Insights</h3>
    <p class="mb-4">
      <strong>Cigna Global</strong> offers strong European coverage with good Croatian network access. Direct relationships with Zagreb hospitals plus full Austrian and German network. Good choice for those wanting comprehensive private access with clear pathways to specialist centers.
    </p>
    <p class="mb-4">
      <strong>Allianz Care</strong> has excellent European presence including strong Austrian and German networks—important given Croatia's referral patterns. Competitive pricing and reliable claims processing. Well-suited for Croatia given proximity to their major markets.
    </p>
    <p class="mb-4">
      <strong>AXA Global</strong> provides solid European coverage at reasonable premiums. Good value for comprehensive benefits. Their continental European network is well-developed.
    </p>
    <p class="mb-4">
      <strong>Bupa Global</strong> offers premium coverage with top service levels. More expensive but comprehensive. Good for those wanting white-glove service and maximum flexibility.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>IMG Global</strong> provides budget-friendly options with flexible coverage. Croatia coverage works through reimbursement at most facilities. Good catastrophic coverage option for those comfortable using HZZO for routine care.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section id="costs" class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Expected Healthcare Costs</h2>
    <p class="mb-4">
      Croatia's healthcare costs are significantly lower than Western Europe—roughly 40-60% less than Germany or Austria. Since adopting the Euro in 2023, pricing is transparent and stable. Private care adds costs but remains affordable by international standards.
    </p>

    <ComparisonTable columns={costColumns} rows={costRows} />

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-800 mb-3 mt-6">Insurance Strategy for Croatia</h3>
    <p class="mb-4">
      Croatia's affordable costs and functional public system create flexibility. You can use HZZO for routine care while maintaining international insurance for private options and European access.
    </p>
    <p class="mb-4">
      <strong>HZZO-focused approach ($3,200-4,500/year):</strong> Enroll in HZZO (~€3,000/year contributions) for public system access. Maintain international insurance primarily for European referrals and travel. Higher deductible international plan keeps costs manageable.
    </p>
    <p class="mb-4">
      <strong>Balanced approach ($5,000-6,500/year):</strong> International insurance with moderate deductible. Use private facilities for most care, HZZO as backup for emergencies. Best for those wanting flexibility without managing two separate systems.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Private-focused approach ($7,500-9,000+/year):</strong> Comprehensive international plan with low deductible. Primary care through private system. May skip HZZO enrollment entirely. Maximum convenience and choice.
    </p>
  </section>

  <CTABox
    title="Get Your Personalized Quote"
    description="Compare plans from multiple international providers. Our advisors understand the emerging Croatia expat community and can help you navigate HZZO integration with international options."
    buttonText="Request Free Quotes"
    buttonHref="/get-quotes"
  />

  <section id="scenarios" class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Real-World Scenarios</h2>
    <p class="mb-4">
      These scenarios illustrate how different insurance setups perform for common situations seniors face in Croatia.
    </p>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Scenario 1: Knee Replacement in Zagreb</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-700 mb-3">
          A 67-year-old living in Split needs knee replacement. Public system wait in Split is 12+ months. Zagreb has shorter waits but requires travel. Private option at Special Hospital Sv. Katarina costs €8,000-10,000.
        </p>
        <p class="text-green-700 font-medium">
          With comprehensive insurance: Private surgery at Sv. Katarina covered after €2,000 deductible. 3-day stay, physiotherapy included. Could alternatively wait for public system at lower cost if timeline isn't critical. Insurance provides choice and speed.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Scenario 2: Complex Cardiac Surgery Requiring Austrian Referral</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-700 mb-3">
          A 70-year-old is diagnosed with complex heart valve condition. Zagreb cardiologists recommend minimally invasive procedure not available in Croatia. AKH Vienna (Vienna General Hospital) suggested.
        </p>
        <p class="text-green-700 font-medium">
          With international insurance including Austria: Referral to AKH Vienna arranged. TAVI procedure (€40,000+) fully covered. Travel assistance provided. 3-hour drive or 1-hour flight from Zagreb. Without European coverage, would face complex self-pay arrangements or wait for less advanced local options.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Scenario 3: Emergency During Island Holiday</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-700 mb-3">
          A 68-year-old vacationing on Hvar island has severe abdominal pain requiring emergency surgery. Nearest major hospital is in Split, a ferry ride away.
        </p>
        <p class="text-amber-700 font-medium">
          With HZZO enrollment: Emergency evacuation to Split covered by coast guard/emergency services. Emergency appendectomy at KBC Split covered through public system with minimal copay. International insurance provides option for private room upgrade and faster follow-up care if desired.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Scenario 4: Cancer Diagnosis and Treatment</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-700 mb-3">
          A 66-year-old is diagnosed with breast cancer. Complete treatment including surgery, chemotherapy, and radiation needed.
        </p>
        <p class="text-green-700 font-medium">
          With comprehensive insurance: Choice of treatment at KBC Zagreb (public, minimal cost) or private oncology care. Full treatment (€50,000+ privately) covered after deductible. Could alternatively choose treatment in Austria or Germany under same policy if preferred. Insurance provides options throughout treatment journey.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Scenario 5: Managing Diabetes Long-Term</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-700 mb-3">
          A 71-year-old manages Type 2 diabetes with quarterly endocrinologist visits, regular blood work, and daily medications.
        </p>
        <p class="text-green-700 font-medium">
          With HZZO enrollment: Regular monitoring through public system with small copays. Medications through HZZO pharmacy list at reduced cost. Annual total: approximately €300-500 through public system. International insurance reserved for private consultations if faster access needed or for complications requiring specialized care.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Scenario 6: Dental Work at Croatian Clinic</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-700 mb-3">
          A 69-year-old needs extensive dental work: multiple crowns, implants, and bridge work. Croatian dental tourism clinics offer complete treatment for €5,000-8,000 vs €15,000+ in Western Europe.
        </p>
        <p class="text-amber-700 font-medium">
          Coverage varies: Most international plans don't cover major dental work (implants, crowns). However, Croatian dental prices are low enough that many pay out-of-pocket and still save significantly. Some plans offer dental add-ons that partially offset costs. Croatia's dental tourism industry means high quality at very competitive prices regardless of insurance.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section id="faqs" class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Common Questions</h2>

    <div class="grid gap-4">
      <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How does Croatia compare to Spain or Portugal for retirement?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-700">
          Croatia offers similar Mediterranean lifestyle at lower costs—roughly 30-40% cheaper than Spain/Portugal. Healthcare quality is comparable for routine care; complex care may require European referral where Spain/Portugal have more domestic capacity. The expat community is smaller and less established. Language barrier is higher—Croatian is harder than Spanish/Portuguese. Croatia suits those wanting authentic European experience without the crowds, willing to trade some infrastructure for lower costs.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What's the difference between coast and Zagreb for healthcare?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-700">
          Zagreb has Croatia's best medical facilities—KBC Zagreb, University Hospital Sisters of Mercy, and most specialists. Coastal cities (Split, Rijeka, Dubrovnik) have good general hospitals but complex cases often transfer to Zagreb. Private options are more numerous in Zagreb. If you have complex health needs, Zagreb provides better immediate access. Coastal living may require occasional travel to Zagreb or acceptance of European referral for serious matters.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Is English sufficient for healthcare?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-700">
          English proficiency is reasonable, especially among younger doctors and in private facilities. Tourist areas along the coast have better English. Zagreb medical centers handling international patients have English-speaking staff. However, Croatian language skills significantly improve healthcare interactions, especially in public facilities. Consider learning basic Croatian, bring a translator app, and ask your insurance if they provide translation support.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How has Euro adoption affected costs?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-700">
          Croatia adopted the Euro in January 2023. Initial concerns about price increases have somewhat materialized—prices rounded up during conversion. However, expats with Euro income now have currency stability and transparency. Healthcare costs in Euro are now directly comparable to other Eurozone countries. Insurance premiums in Euro/USD provide predictability. Overall, Euro adoption simplified financial planning for expats.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What about prescriptions and medications?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-700">
          Pharmacies (ljekarna) are well-distributed with good medication availability. HZZO enrollees access the essential medications list at reduced prices. Private prescriptions are available but more expensive. Prices are generally 30-50% below US costs. Specialty medications may require ordering or import. Most common chronic condition medications are readily available. International insurance plans with prescription coverage can offset costs.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What's the expat retirement community like?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-700">
          Croatia's expat retirement community is smaller but growing. Split and Dubrovnik have the most established international presence. Zagreb attracts business expats who sometimes stay for retirement. Online communities and Facebook groups help connect newcomers. The community is more European than American—many German, Austrian, and Northern European retirees. The smaller community means fewer English-language services but also more authentic integration with Croatian life.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <CTABox
    title="Ready for Croatian Retirement?"
    description="Get personalized health insurance quotes from providers experienced with emerging European destinations. Compare coverage options and find the right plan for your Adriatic coast retirement."
    buttonText="Get Your Free Quote"
    buttonHref="/get-quotes"
    variant="highlight"
  />
</PageShell>
